items.abstract: <jats:p>We present data on the interaction of arginine-rich peptides of human immunodeficiency virus (HIV-Tat) with tRNA<jats:sup>Phe</jats:sup> of <jats:italic>Saccharomyces cerevisiae</jats:italic>. We have found that tRNA forms complexes with the Tat1 peptide of amino acid sequence GRKK<jats:underline>R</jats:underline>RQRRRA and its mutants where <jats:underline>R</jats:underline> is replaced by D-arginine, citrulline or ornithine. The structure of tRNA-Tat1 complex was probed by specific RNases digestions and Pb<jats:sup>2+</jats:sup>-induced cleavage of phosphodiester bond of guanosine. The nucleotide sequence UGGG located in the dihydrouridine loop of tRNA<jats:sup>Phe</jats:sup> binds to Tat peptide and therefore is specifically protected against RNases and is not hydrolyzed by Pb<jats:sup>2+ </jats:sup>ion. It seems that the peptide-RNA complex formation depends on direct recognition of guanine moieties of tRNA with arginine residues. These interactions are similar to those observed in many DNA-protein complexes, but are different from those previously observed for TAR RNA-Tat complexes.</jats:p>
title: Interaction of HIV Tat Peptides With tRNAPhe from Yeast
